Never mix your mushroom extracts anywhere near your chlorine dioxide drops or your high-dose morning fire-cider shot. The oxidation reaction will ruin the potency of the mushrooms before your body can absorb them.\
\
=======================================\
Creation of Unknown Subcellular Toxins\
======================================\
\
Methylene Blue is a complex aromatic chemical ring structure. When a powerful, unselective oxidant like Chlorine Dioxide attacks it inside the bottle, it doesn't just turn it clear into Leucomethylene Blue\'97it begins breaking the molecular ring apart.This structural degradation can create fragmented chlorinated organic compounds. Driving unknown, unstudied chemical fragments directly into your bloodstream via DMSO skips your digestive tract's protective filtering barriers, placing an immediate, silent detoxifying workload on your liver and kidneys.\
\
\
==================================================\
Precipitated Copper Aggregation (Heavy Metal Pooling)\
====================================================\
\
In a neutral, stable liquid, your Copper Sulfate dissolves into free copper ions (Cu\'b2\uc0\u8314 ) that your skin can absorb. However, the aggressive chemical reaction occurring between Chlorine Dioxide and Methylene Blue alters the local pH and electrical charge of the entire solution.This environment can cause the copper ions to bind together and precipitate into microscopic heavy-metal clusters. Instead of absorbing smoothly into your bloodstream, these aggregated copper clusters can pool heavily inside the local skin tissue, causing deep dermal discoloration and localized heavy metal toxicity.\
\
An analysis of your specified percentages shows that while your 70% DMSO is a standard, clinically recognized concentration for topical absorption, your 3% Chlorine Dioxide (\\(ClO_\{2\}\\)) and 5% Copper Sulfate (\\(CuSO_\{4\}\\)) are extremely concentrated for direct skin application.When carried deep into your tissue by a 70% DMSO solvent, these high percentages create an aggressive chemical environment that can cause localized skin damage, chronic dermal inflammation, or trace mineral over-saturation over time [1.5, 1.6].To protect your skin while maximizing the effectiveness of your protocol, let's examine the empirical safety limits for each compound and look at how to dilute your mixtures to safer, more sustainable levels.\
\
===================================================\
Empirical Review of Percentages
\f2 \uc0\u9888 \u65039 
\f0 \
===================================================\
\
Chlorine Dioxide (\\(ClO_\{2\}\\)) at 3% (Extremely High)The Reality: A 3% solution is equal to 30,000 parts per million (ppm). In clinical dermatology and wound-care research, topical solutions of chlorine dioxide are safely used at concentrations closer to 20 to 50 ppm (roughly 0.005%).The Risk: Applying 30,000 ppm of \\(ClO_\{2\}\\) directly to your skin introduces a massive oxidative load. When driven past your skin barrier by DMSO, it can cause deep, chemical dermal bleaching, cellular irritation, and structural damage to the surrounding healthy tissue [1.5].\
\

\f2 \uc0\u9888 \u65039 
\f0  Copper Sulfate (\\(CuSO_\{4\}\\)) at 5% (Very High)The Reality: A 5% copper sulfate solution is highly concentrated. In agricultural and chemical research, a 5% mix is used as a potent antimicrobial or antifungal wash. For safe topical human absorption, copper peptide solutions are typically formulated at fractions of a percent (often between 0.1% and 0.5%).The Risk: Free copper ions are highly reactive. Forcing a 5% concentration deep into your subcutaneous tissue via DMSO bypasses your liver's standard regulatory systems, increasing the risk of localized heavy metal pooling, skin discoloration, and chronic dermal irritation [1.6].\
\

\f2 \uc0\u9888 \u65039 
\f0  Methylene Blue (MB) (Over-Concentrated)The Reality: Methylene Blue has a specific biochemical curve. At very low, diluted concentrations (nanomolar to low micromolar ranges, or roughly 0.01% to 0.1%), it acts as a powerful mitochondrial antioxidant and electron cycler.\
\
The Risk: If you "overdo" the concentration, Methylene Blue flips its mechanism and becomes a pro-oxidant. Instead of protecting your cells, a high concentration creates massive oxidative stress, generating free radicals that can damage the very neural and vascular pathways you are trying to heal.\
\
